(99, 8, 'html-semantic-elements', 'HTML5 semantic elements', '<h1>HTML5 semantic element</h1><div><b>Semantics = meaning.</b></div><div><br></div><div><b>Semantic element</b> = the meaning of the element.</div><div><br></div><div><span style=\"color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 30px;\">What is a semantic element?</span></div><div>A semantic element can clearly describe its meaning to browsers and developers.</div><div><br></div><div>No semantic &nbsp;element instances: &lt;div&gt; and &lt;span&gt; - no need to think about content.</div><div><br></div><div>Examples of semantic elements: &lt;form&gt;, &lt;table&gt;, and &lt;img&gt; - clearly define its contents.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Browser support</b></div><div><b><br></b></div><div><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"1476412457871079.jpg\" style=\"width: 189px;\"><br></div><div><br></div><div>Internet Explorer 9+, Firefox, Chrome, Safari, and Opera support semantic elements.</div><div><br></div><div>Note: This element is not supported in Internet Explorer 8 and earlier. However, a compatible workaround is provided at the bottom of the article.</div><div><br></div><h2>New semantic elements in HTML5</h2><div>Many existing websites contain the following HTML code: &lt;div id=\"nav\"&gt;, &lt;div class=\"header\"&gt;, or &lt;div id=\"footer\"&gt; to indicate the navigation link, header, and trailer.</div><div><br></div><div>HTML5 provides new semantic elements to clarify different parts of a web page:</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><table width=\"-642\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; color: rgb(20, 25, 30); font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, &quot;PingFang SC&quot;, 微软雅黑, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; background-color: rgb(237, 241, 242);\"><tbody style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><tr class=\"firstRow\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\" style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); word-break: break-all; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;\"><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;header&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;nav&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;section&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;article&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;aside&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;figcaption&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;figure&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><font style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: inherit;\">&lt;footer&gt;</font></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><br style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"></p></td><td width=\"193\" valign=\"top\" style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); word-break: break-all; border-width: 1px; border-style: solid;\"><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"></p><p style=\"margin-top: 0.5em; margin-bottom: 0.5em; padding: 5px 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 12px; color: rgb(31, 36, 38); line-height: 1.6;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"sdffg.jpg\" style=\"width: 225.994px;\"><br style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p style=\"margin-top: 2px; margin-bottom: 2px; padding: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 1.8em; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 1.8em; border: 0px; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, STHeiti, &quot;Microsoft Yahei&quot;, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 18px;\"></span></p><hr style=\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; height: 1px; border-top: 0px; clear: both; background-color: rgb(230, 230, 230); color: rgb(20, 25, 30); font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, &quot;PingFang SC&quot;, 微软雅黑, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif;\"><p style=\"margin-top: 2px; margin-bottom: 2px; padding: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); font-size: 1.8em; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); line-height: 1.8em; border: 0px; font-family: &quot;Open Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, STHeiti, &quot;Microsoft Yahei&quot;, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 18px;\"></span></p></div><div><span style=\"color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 30px;\">HTML5 &lt;header&gt; element</span></div><div>The &lt;header&gt; element describes the header area of ​​the document</div><div><br></div><div>The &lt;header&gt; element takes care of the presentation area used to define the content.</div><div><br></div><div>You can use multiple &lt;header&gt; elements in the page.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example defines the head of the article:</div><div><br></div>\n\n<form><textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; \n&lt;html&gt; \n&lt;head&gt;  \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt; \n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;  \n&lt;/head&gt; \n&lt;body&gt; \n&lt;article&gt; \n    &lt;header&gt; \n        &lt; H1&gt;Internet Explorer 9&lt;/h1&gt; \n        &lt;p&gt;&lt;time pubdate datetime=\"2016-10-15\"&gt;&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/p&gt; \n    &lt;/header&gt; \n    &lt;p&gt; Windows Internet Explorer 9 (abbreviated IE9) is &lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;/article&gt; \n&lt;/body&gt; \n&lt;/html&gt; \n\n</textarea></form>\n\n<div>&nbsp;</div><div>Pubdate indicates that the date/time in the &lt;time&gt; element is the publication date of the document (or the most recent senior &lt;article&gt; element) &nbsp; &nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Run the program and try it out&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><h2>HTML5 &lt;nav&gt; element</h2><div>The &lt;nav&gt; tag defines the part of the navigation link.</div><div><br></div><div>The &lt;nav&gt; element is used to define the navigation link partial area of ​​the page, but not all links need to be included in the &lt;nav&gt; element!</div><div><br></div><div>Instance</div>\n\n<form><textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; \n&lt;html&gt; \n&lt;head&gt;  \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt; \n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;  \n&lt;/head&gt; \n&lt;body&gt; \n&lt;nav&gt; \n    &lt;a href= \"\"&gt;HTML&lt;/a&gt; | \n    &lt;a href=\"\"&gt;CSS&lt;/a&gt; | \n    &lt;a href=\"\"&gt;JavaScript&lt;/a&gt; | \n    &lt;a href=\"\"&gt;jQuery&lt;/a&gt; \n&lt;/nav &gt; \n&lt;/body&gt; \n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea></form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><span style=\"color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 30px;\"><br>HTML5 &lt;section&gt; element</span></div><div>The &lt;section&gt; tag defines the section (section, section) in the document. Such as chapters, headers, footers, or other parts of the document.</div><div><br></div><div>According to the W3C HTML5 documentation: section contains a set of content and its title.</div><div><br></div><div>Instance</div><div><br></div>\n\n<form><textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; \n&lt;html&gt; \n&lt;head&gt;  \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt; \n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;  \n&lt;/head&gt; \n&lt;body&gt; \n&lt;section&gt; \n    &lt;h1&gt;WWF &lt;/h1&gt; \n    &lt;p&gt;The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) is an international organization dedicated to protecting issues, researching and restoring the environment, the predecessor of the World Wildlife Fund. WWF was founded in 1961. &lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;/section&gt; \n&lt;section&gt; \n    &lt;h1&gt;WWF\'s Panda symbol&lt;/h1&gt; \n    &lt;p&gt;Panda has become a symbol of WWF. The famous Panda World Wildlife Fund logo comes from a panda named Devil, built from the Beijing Zoo of the Beijing Zoo in the same year. &lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;/section&gt; \n&lt;/body&gt; \n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea></form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><span style=\"color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 30px;\"><br>HTML5 &lt;article&gt; element</span></div><div>The &lt;article&gt; tag defines separate content. .</div><div><br></div><div>&lt;article&gt; element usage example:</div><div><br></div><div>Forum post (forum posts)</div><div><br></div><div>Blog post (blog)</div><div><br></div><div>News story</div><div><br></div><div>Comment</div><div><br></div><div>Instance</div><div><br></div>\n\n<form><textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; \n&lt;html&gt; \n&lt;head&gt;  \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt; \n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;  \n&lt;/head&gt; \n&lt;body&gt; \n&lt;article&gt; \n    &lt;h1&gt;Internet Explorer 9&lt;/h1&gt; \n    &lt;p&gt; Windows Internet Explorer 9 (abbreviated IE9) was released on March 14, 2011 at 21:00. &lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;/article&gt; \n&lt;/body&gt; \n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea>\n\n</form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>HTML5 &lt;aside&gt; element</h2><div>The &lt;aside&gt; tag defines content outside of the main area of ​​the page (such as the sidebar).</div><div><br></div><div>The content of the aside tag should be related to the content of the main area.</div><div><br></div><div>Instance</div>\n\n<form>\n<textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; \n&lt;html&gt; \n&lt;head&gt;  \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt; \n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;  \n&lt;/head&gt; \n&lt;body&gt; \n&lt;p&gt;I like it very much Php Chinese network (jquerylearn.com) learning HTML knowledge&lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;aside&gt; \n    &lt;h2&gt;php Chinese network (jquerylearn.com)&lt;/h2&gt; \n    &lt;p&gt;php Chinese network (jquerylearn.com) has a lot of PHP and HTML Tutorial&lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;/aside&gt; \n&lt;/body&gt; \n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea></form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>HTML5 &lt;footer&gt; element</h2><div>The &lt;footer&gt; element describes the bottom area of ​​the document.</div><div><br></div><div>The &lt;footer&gt; element should contain its containing elements</div><div><br></div><div>A footer usually contains the author of the document, copyright information, terms of use of the link, contact information, etc.</div><div><br></div><div>You can use multiple &lt;footer&gt; elements in the document.</div><div><br></div><div>Instance</div><div><br></div>\n\n<form><textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; \n&lt;html&gt; \n&lt;head&gt;  \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt; \n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;  \n&lt;/head&gt; \n&lt;body&gt; \n&lt;footer&gt; \n    &lt;p&gt;Publish People: Liu Qi&lt;/p&gt; \n    &lt;p&gt;&lt;time pubdate datetime=\"2016-10-15\"&gt;&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;/footer&gt; \n&lt;/body&gt; \n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea></form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>HTML5 &lt;figure&gt; and &lt;figcaption&gt; elements</h2><div>The &lt;figure&gt; tag specifies separate stream content (images, charts, photos, code, etc.).</div><div><br></div><div>The content of the &lt;figure&gt; element should be related to the main content, but if it is deleted, it should not affect the document flow.</div><div><br></div><div>The &lt;figcaption&gt; tag defines the title of the &lt;figure&gt; element.</div><div><br></div><div>The &lt;figcaption&gt; element should be placed at the position of the first or last child of the \"figure\" element.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Instance</b></div>\n\n<form>\n <textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; \n&lt;html&gt; \n&lt;head&gt;  \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt; \n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;  \n    &lt;!--[if lt IE 9]&gt; \n    &lt;script src =\"html5shiv.js\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt; \n    &lt;![endif]--&gt; \n&lt;/head&gt; \n&lt;body&gt; \n\n&lt;p&gt;Huangshan: World Heritage and Nature Double Heritage, World Geopark, National AAAAA Level Scenic Spot, National Level Scenic spots, the national civilization scenic tourist area demonstration site, China\'s top ten famous mountains, the world\'s first Qishan. Huangshan is located in Huangshan City, southern Anhui Province&lt;/p&gt; \n\n&lt;figure&gt; \n    &lt;img src=\"http://images.tuniu.com/images/2013-04-07/1/1X52RthA3c9Y5pHv.jpg\" alt=\"黄山风景\" Width=\"304\" height=\"228\"&gt; \n    &lt;figcaption&gt;Fig.1 - A landscape view of Huangshan.&lt;/figcaption&gt; \n&lt;/figure&gt; \n\n&lt;/body&gt; \n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea> \n</form>\n \n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><h2>Can we start using these semantic elements?</h2><div>The above elements are all block elements (except &lt;figcaption&gt;).</div><div><br></div><div>In order for these blocks and elements to work in all versions of the browser, you need to set the properties in the stylesheet file (the following style code allows older browsers to support the block-level elements covered in this chapter):</div><div><br></div><div>Put it in the middle of &lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;</div>\n\n<textarea class=\"code\">&lt;style&gt; \n   header, section, footer, aside, nav, article, figure \n   { \n       display: block; \n   } \n&lt;/style&gt; \n</textarea>\n\n\n<div><br></div><h2>Issues in Internet Explorer 8 and earlier versions of IE</h2><div><br></div><div>IE8 and earlier versions of IE cannot render CSS effects in these elements, so you can\'t use &lt;header&gt;, &lt;section&gt;, &lt;footer&gt;, &lt;aside&gt;, &lt;nav&gt;, &lt;article&gt;, &lt;figure&gt;, or other HTML5 elements.</div><div><br></div><div>Solution: You can use the HTML5 Shiv Javascript script to solve IE compatibility issues. HTML5 Shiv download address: http://code.google.com/p/html5shiv/</div><div><br></div><div>Once downloaded, place the following code in the page:</div><div><br></div><div><b>&lt;!--[if lt IE 9]&gt;&nbsp;</b></div><div><b>&lt;script src=\"html5shiv.js\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;&nbsp;</b></div><div><b>&lt;![endif]--&gt;</b></div><div><br></div><div>The above code will load the html5shiv.js file when the browser is smaller than the IE9 version. You must place it in the &lt;head&gt; element, because IE needs to render these HTML5 new elements after the header is loaded.</div>', 'HTML,CSS,JavaScript,SQL,PHP,jQuery,XML,DOM,Bootstrap,Python,Web development,W3C,tutorials,programming,training,learning,quiz,primer,lessons,references,examples,source code,colors,demos,tips', 'HTML5 semantic elements | jquerylearn.com', 'A semantic element can clearly describe its meaning to browsers and developers.No semantic  element instances: <div> and <span> - no need to think about content.Examples of semantic elements: <form>, <table>, and <img> - clearly define its contents.', '2018-07-06 12:32:44', 'akshay'),
(100, 8, 'html-web-storage', 'HTML5 Web Storage', '		  		  		  		  		   <h1>What is HTML5 Web Storage?</h1><div>Using HTML5 to store user browsing data locally is a better way to store locally than cookies.</div><div><br></div><div>Earlier, local storage used cookies. But Web storage needs to be more secure and fast. The data is not stored on the server, but the data is only used by users to request website data. It can also store large amounts of data without affecting the performance of the website.</div><div><br></div><div>The data exists as a key/value pair, and the data of the web page only allows the web page to be accessed.</div><div><b><br></b></div><div><b>Browser support</b></div><div><br></div><div><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"1476412457871079.jpg\" style=\"width: 189px;\"><br></div><div><br></div><div>Internet Explorer 8+, Firefox, Opera, Chrome, and Safari support web storage.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Note </b>: Web storage is not supported in Internet Explorer 7 and earlier versions of IE.</div><div><br></div><div><b>localStorage </b>and <b>sessionStorage&nbsp;</b></div><div><br></div><div>There are two new objects that store data on the client:</div><div><br></div><div><b>localStorage </b>- data storage without time limit</div><div><br></div><div><b>sessionStorage </b>- data storage for a session</div><div><br></div><div>Before using web storage, you should check if your browser supports localStorage and sessionStorage:</div><div><br></div>\n\n<textarea class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 662px; height: 207px;\">If(typeof(Storage)!==\"undefined\") \n{ \n   // sessionStorage localStorage support! \n   // Related code..... \n} \nelse \n{ \n   // Sorry, web storage is not supported \n}\n\n</textarea>\n\n<div><span style=\"color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 30px;\"><br>localStorage object</span></div><div>There is no time limit for the data stored by the <b>localStorage </b>object. After the second day, the second week or the next year, the data is still available.</div><div><br></div>\n\n<form><textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt; \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt; \n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"result\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n    if(typeof(Storage)!==\"undefined\")\n    {\n        localStorage.lastname=\"Dhiman\";\n        document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML=\"name: \" + localStorage.lastname;\n    }\n    else\n    {\n        document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML=\"your browser does not support web storage...\";\n    }\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n</textarea>\n\n</form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><div>Instance resolution:</div><div><br></div><div>Create a localStorage key/value pair using key=\"lastname\" and value=\"Smith\"</div><div><br></div><div>Retrieve the value of the key value \"lastname\" and insert the data into the element of id=\"result\"</div><div><br></div><div>Tip : Key/value pairs are usually stored as strings, and you can convert the format to suit your needs.&nbsp;<br><br></div><div>The following example shows the number of times a user clicked a button. The string value in the code is converted to a numeric type:</div><div><br></div>\n\n<form>\n<textarea class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 782px; height: 492px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt; \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt; \n    &lt;script&gt;\n        function clickCounter()\n        {\n            if(typeof(Storage)!==\"undefined\")\n            {\n                if (localStorage.clickcount)\n                {\n                    localStorage.clickcount=Number(localStorage.clickcount)+1;\n                }\n                else\n                {\n                    localStorage.clickcount=1;\n                }\n                document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML=\" Click the button \" + localStorage.clickcount + \" time(s).\";\n            }\n            else\n            {\n                document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML=\"Sorry, your browser does not support web storage...\";            }\n        }\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;button onclick=\"clickCounter()\" type=\"button\"&gt;Click&lt;/button&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"result\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Click this button to see the counter increase. &lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;p&gt;Close the browser tab (or window) and try again, the counter will continue to count (not reset). &lt;/p&gt; \n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea>\n</form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><h2>sessionStorage object</h2><div>The sessionStorage method stores data for a session. When the user closes the browser window, the data is deleted.</div><div><br></div><div>How to create and access a sessionStorage::</div><div><br></div>\n\n<form>\n<textarea class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt; \n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;jquerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt; \n    &lt;script&gt;\n        function clickCounter()\n        {\n            if(typeof(Storage)!==\"undefined\")\n            {\n                if (sessionStorage.clickcount)\n                {\n                    sessionStorage.clickcount=Number(sessionStorage.clickcount)+1;\n                }\n                else\n                {\n                    sessionStorage.clickcount=1;\n                }\n                document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML=\" Click the button \" + sessionStorage.clickcount + \" time(s) \";\n            }\n            else\n            {\n                document.getElementById(\"result\").innerHTML=\"Sorry, your browser does not support web storage...\";\n            }\n        }\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;button onclick=\"clickCounter()\" type=\"button\"&gt;Click&lt;/button&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"result\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Click this button to see the counter increment.&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Close the browser tab (or window), try again, reset the counter&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n\n</textarea>\n</form>\n\n<div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div>\n		   \n		   \n		   \n		   \n		  ', 'HTML5 Web Storage.HTML Web StorageHTML 5, Tutorials, Forms-2 Learning, Beginners,Canvas, Audio, Video, New Semantic Elements, Geolocation, Persistent Local Storage, Web Storage, Web SQL, Forms 2.0, Microdata and Drag and Drop, IndexedDB, Web messaging, CORS, Web RTC, Canvas Drawing Rectangles, Web Storage, Server Sent Events, Web Canvas, Web Workers, Slide Desk.', 'HTML5 Web Storage | jquerylearn.com', ' Using HTML5 to store user browsing data locally is a better way to store locally than cookies.\n\nEarlier, local storage used cookies. But Web storage needs to be more secure and fast. The data is not stored on the server, but the data is only used by users to request website data. It can also store large amounts of data without affecting the performance of the website. ', '2018-07-06 12:32:44', 'akshay');
