(173, 11, 'jquery-event', 'What is an event?', '		  <p>		  </p><h1>What is an event ?</h1><div><br></div><div><div>The response of the page to different visitors is called an event.</div><div><br></div><div>An event handler refers to the method that is called when certain events occur in the HTML.</div><div><br></div><div>Example:</div><div><br></div><div>Move the mouse over the element.</div><div><br></div><div>Select radio button</div><div><br></div><div>Click element</div><div><br></div><div>The term \"trigger\" (or \"excitation\") is often used in events such as: \"The keypress event is triggered when you press a button.\"</div><div><br></div><div>Common DOM events:</div><div><br></div><div><br></div></div><div><table border=\"1\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><tbody style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><tr class=\"firstRow\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><th style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 5px 10px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); border: 1px solid rgb(221, 221, 221);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Event</span></th><th style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 5px 10px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); border: 1px solid rgb(221, 221, 221);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Description</span></th></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Click</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">This event is fired when the mouse clicks</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Keypress</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Triggered when the key on the keyboard is pressed again</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Submit</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Triggered when the form is submitted</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Load</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Page loaded trigger</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Dblclick</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Double click on the mouse is triggered</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Keydown</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Triggered when a key on the keyboard is pressed</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Change</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Triggered when the current element loses focus and the content of the element changes</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Resize</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Triggered when the browser window size is changed</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Mouseenter</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Add/trigger mouseenter event</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Keyup</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Triggered when the key on the keyboard is pressed and released</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Focus</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Triggered when an element loses focus</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Scroll</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Add/trigger scroll event</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Mouseleave</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Add/trigger mouseleave event</span></td></tr><tr style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\"><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0);\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Blur</span></td><td style=\"margin: 0px; -webkit-tap-highlight-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0); word-break: break-all;\"><span style=\"vertical-align: inherit;\">Add/trigger blur event</span><br></td></tr></tbody></table></div> \n		  \n<p></p><p><br></p><h2>jQuery event method syntax</h2><p><br></p><p>In jQuery, most DOM events have an equivalent jQuery method.</p><p><br></p><p>Specify a click event in the page:</p><p><br></p><p><b>$(\"p\").click();</b></p><p><br></p><p>The next step is to define what time to trigger the event. You can do this with an event function:</p><p><br></p><pre>$(\"p\").click(function(){&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; // Code executed after the action is fired!!&nbsp;<br>});</pre><p><br></p><h2>Commonly used jQuery event methods</h2><p><br></p><p><b>$(document).ready()</b></p><p><br></p><p>The $(document).ready() method allows us to execute the function after the document has been completely loaded. This event method has already been mentioned in the jQuery syntax section.</p><p><br></p><h2><b>Click()</b></h2><p>The click() method is called when a button click event is fired.</p><p>This function is executed when the user clicks on an HTML element.</p><p>In the following example, when the click event fires on a &lt;p&gt; element, the current &lt;p&gt; element is hidden:</p><p></p><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 450px; height: 442px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt; \n&lt;title&gt;jQuerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt; \n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n$(document).ready(function(){\n  $(\"p\").click(function(){\n    $(this).hide();\n  });\n   \n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;If you point me, I will disappear. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Click me to disappear!&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;I also disappeared!&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form><p></p><p>Run the program and try it out</p><p><br></p><h2>Dblclick()</h2><p><br></p><p>The dblclick event occurs when you double-click an element.</p><p>The dblclick() method fires a dblclick event, or a function that runs when a dblclick event occurs:</p><p><br></p><p></p><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 394px; height: 407px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt; \n&lt;title&gt;jQuerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt; \n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n$(document).ready(function(){\n  $(\"p\").dblclick(function(){\n    $(this).hide();\n  });\n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Double click the left mouse button and I will disappear. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Double click and I disappear! &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Double click and I will disappear! &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form><p></p>&nbsp;<br><p>Run the program and try it out</p><p><br></p><h2>Mouseenter()</h2><p><br></p><p>The mouseenter event occurs when the mouse pointer passes through the element.</p><p><br></p><p>The mouseenter() method fires a mouseenter event or specifies a function that runs when a mouseenter event occurs:</p><p><br></p><p></p><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt; \n&lt;title&gt;jQuerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt; \n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n$(document).ready(function(){\n  $(\"#p1\").mouseenter(function(){\n    alert(\"Your mouse has been moved to the element of id=p1!\");\n  });\n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p id=\"p1\"&gt;The mouse pointer enters here and you will see a pop-up window. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form><p></p><p><br></p><p>Run the program and try it out</p><p><br></p><h2>Mousedown()</h2><p><br></p><p>The mousedown event occurs when the mouse pointer moves over the element and the mouse button is pressed.</p><p><br></p><p>The mousedown() method fires a mousedown event or specifies a function that runs when a mousedown event occurs:</p><p><br></p><p></p><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt; \n&lt;title&gt;jQuerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt; \n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n$(document).ready(function(){\n  $(\"#p1\").mousedown(function(){\n    alert (\"mouse pressed on this paragraph!\");\n  });\n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p id=\"p1\"&gt;This is a paragraph&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form><p></p><p><br></p><p>Run the program and try it out</p><p><br></p><h2>Hover()</h2><p><br></p><p>The hover() method is used to simulate a cursor hover event.</p><p><br></p><p>When the mouse is moved over the element, the first function specified (mouseenter) is fired; when the mouse is moved out of the element, the specified second function (mouseleave) is triggered.</p><p></p><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n$(document).ready(function(){\n  $(\"#p1\").hover(function(){\n    alert (\"You entered p1!\");\n    },\n    Function(){\n    alert (\"bye! Now you have left p1!\");\n  }); \n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p id=\"p1\"&gt;This is a paragraph. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form><br><p></p><p>Run the program and try it out</p><p><br></p><h2>Focus()</h2><p><br></p><p>The focus event occurs when the element gets focus.</p><p><br></p><p>When you click on a selected element with a mouse click or navigate to an element with the tab key, that element gets the focus.</p><p><br></p><p>The focus() method fires a focus event or specifies a function that runs when a focus event occurs:</p><p></p><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 540px; height: 429px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;jQuerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"input\").focus(function(){\n                $(this).css(\"background-color\",\"#cccccc\");\n            });\n            $(\"input\").blur(function(){\n                $(this).css(\"background-color\",\"#ffffff\");\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\nName: &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"fullname\"&gt;&lt;br&gt;\nEmail: &lt;input type=\"text\" name=\"email\"&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form><br><p></p><p>Run the program and try it out</p><p><br></p><p>Interested to try other events</p><p><br></p> \n		  ', '', 'What is an event?', '               ', '2018-11-24 14:47:00', 'Akshay'),
(175, 12, 'jquery-hide-show', 'jQuery hide and show', '		  <h1>jQuery hide and show</h1><h2>jQuery hide() and show()</h2><div><br></div><div>With jQuery, you can hide and display HTML elements using the hide() and show() methods:</div><div><br></div><div>Instance</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 395px; height: 318px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"#hide\").click(function(){\n                $(\"p\").hide();\n            });\n            $(\"#show\").click(function(){\n                $(\"p\").show();\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;If you click the \"Hide\" button, I will disappear. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;button id=\"hide\"&gt;Hide&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;button id=\"show\"&gt;Show&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>Grammar:</h2><div><br></div><pre>$(selector).hide(speed,callback);&nbsp;</pre><div><br></div><pre>$(selector).show(speed,callback);</pre><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the speed of the hide/show, which can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after the display is hidden or displayed.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the hide() method with the speed parameter:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 464px; height: 401px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"p\").hide(1000);\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Hide&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Life is about making choices. Once you make your choice, you must live in your decision. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery toggle()</h2><div><br></div><div>With jQuery, you can toggle the hide() and show() methods with the toggle() method.</div><div><br></div><div>Show hidden elements and hide the displayed elements:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"p\").toggle();\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Hide/Show&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;The real failure is not that you have not done anything, but that you are willing to fail. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Everything will be fine, even if it is not today, there will be one day. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>Grammar:</h2><div><br></div><pre>$(selector).toggle(speed,callback);</pre><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the speed of the hide/show, which can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after the toggle() method completes.</div><div><br></div> \n		  ', '', 'jQuery hide and show', '                 ', '2018-11-24 14:03:46', 'Akshay'),
(176, 12, 'jquery-fadein-out', 'jQuery fades in and out', '		  		  <h1>jQuery fades in and out</h1><div>With jQuery, you can achieve the fade in and out of the element.</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery Fading method</h2><div><br></div><div>With jQuery, you can achieve the fade in and out of the element.</div><div><br></div><div>jQuery has the following four fade methods:</div><div><br></div><div>fadeIn()</div><div><br></div><div>fadeOut()</div><div><br></div><div>fadeToggle()</div><div><br></div><div>fadeTo()</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery fadeIn() method</h2><div><br></div><div>jQuery fadeIn() is used to fade in hidden elements.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Grammar</b>:</div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).fadeIn(speed,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds. .</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after fading is completed.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the fadeIn() method with different parameters:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 479px; height: 481px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#div1\").fadeIn();\n                $(\"#div2\").fadeIn(\"slow\");\n                $(\"#div3\").fadeIn(3000);\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;The following example demonstrates the effect of using different parameters for fadeIn(). &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Click to fade in the div element. &lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div1\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;display:none;background-color:red;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;display:none;background-color:green;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div3\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;display:none;background-color:blue;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery fadeOut() method</h2><div><br></div><div>The jQuery fadeOut() method is used to fade out visible elements.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Grammar:</b></div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).fadeOut(speed,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after fading is completed.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the fadeOut() method with different parameters:<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#div1\").fadeOut();\n                $(\"#div2\").fadeOut(\"slow\");\n                $(\"#div3\").fadeOut(3000);\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;The following example demonstrates the effect of fadeOut() using different parameters. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Click to fade out the div element. &lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div1\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:red;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:green;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div3\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:blue;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery fadeToggle() method</h2><div><br></div><div>The jQuery fadeToggle() method toggles between the fadeIn() and fadeOut() methods.</div><div><br></div><div>If the element has faded out, fadeToggle() adds a fade in effect to the element.</div><div><br></div><div>If the element has faded in, fadeToggle() adds a fade-out effect to the element.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Grammar</b>:</div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).fadeToggle(speed,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after fading is completed.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the fadeToggle() method with different parameters:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 798px; height: 523px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;jQuerylearn.com&lt;/title&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#div1\").fadeToggle();\n                $(\"#div2\").fadeToggle(\"slow\");\n                $(\"#div3\").fadeToggle(3000);\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\nThe &lt;p&gt; example demonstrates that fadeToggle() uses different speed parameters. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;click fade in/out&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div1\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:red;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:green;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div3\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:blue;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery fadeTo() method</h2><div><br></div><div>The jQuery fadeTo() method allows the gradient to be a given opacity (values ​​between 0 and 1).</div><div><br></div><div>grammar:</div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).fadeTo(speed,opacity,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The required speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The required opacity parameter in the fadeTo() method sets the fade effect to the given opacity (values ​​between 0 and 1).</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after the function completes.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the fadeTo() method with different parameters:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 792px; height: 198px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n$(document).ready(function(){\n  $(\"button\").click(function(){\n    $(\"#div1\").fadeTo(\"slow\",0.15);\n    $(\"#div2\").fadeTo(\"slow\",0.4);\n    $(\"#div3\").fadeTo(\"slow\",0.7);\n  });\n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Show fadeTo() with different parameters&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;button&gt; point I let the color fade&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div1\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:red;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:green;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div3\" style=\"width:80px;height:80px;background-color:blue;\"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div> \n		   \n		  ', '', 'jQuery fades in and out', '                   ', '2018-11-24 14:14:49', 'Akshay'),
(177, 12, 'jquery-slide', 'jQuery slide', '<h1>jQuery slide</h1><div>The jQuery slide method causes the element to slide up and down.</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery sliding method</h2><div><br></div><div>With jQuery, you can create a sliding effect on an element.</div><div><br></div><div>jQuery has the following sliding methods:</div><div><br></div><div>slideDown()</div><div><br></div><div>slideUp()</div><div><br></div><div>slideToggle()</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery slideDown() method</h2><div><br></div><div>The jQuery slideDown() method is used to swipe an element down.</div><div><br></div><div>grammar:</div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).slideDown(speed,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after the swipe is complete.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the slideDown() method:</div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 613px; height: 590px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"#div1\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#div2\").slideDown(\"slow\");\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;style type=\"text/css\"&gt;\n        #Div2, #div1\n        {\n            padding:5px;\n            text-align:center;\n            background-color:#e5eecc;\n            border:solid 1px #c3c3c3;\n        }\n        #div2\n        {\n            padding:50px;\n            display:none;\n        }\n    &lt;/style&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div1\"&gt;Click me to slide down the panel&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\"&gt;Hello, beauty/handsome&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Run and try it out</div><h2>jQuery slideUp() method</h2><div><br></div><div>The jQuery slideUp() method is used to slide the element up.</div><div><br></div><div>grammar:</div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).slideUp(speed,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after the swipe is complete.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the slideUp() method:&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 558px; height: 496px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt; \n$(document).ready(function(){\n  $(\"#div1\").click(function(){\n    $(\"#div2\").slideUp(\"slow\");\n  });\n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n \n&lt;style type=\"text/css\"&gt; \n# Div2, # div1\n{\npadding:5px;\ntext-align:center;\nbackground-color:#e5eecc;\nborder:solid 1px #c3c3c3;\n}\n# div2\n{\npadding:50px;\n}\n&lt;/style&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n \n&lt;div id=\"div1\"&gt;Click me to pull up the panel&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\"&gt;Hello world!&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery slideToggle() method</h2><div><br></div><div>The jQuery slideToggle() method toggles between the slideDown() and slideUp() methods.</div><div><br></div><div>If the element slides down, slideToggle() can slide them up.</div><div><br></div><div>If the element slides up, slideToggle() can slide them down.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Grammar</b></div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).slideToggle(speed,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after the swipe is complete.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the slideToggle() method:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 613px; height: 650px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"#div1\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#div2\").slideToggle(\"slow\");\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;style type=\"text/css\"&gt;\n        # Div2, # div1\n        {\n            padding:5px;\n            text-align:center;\n            background-color:#e5eecc;\n            border:solid 1px #c3c3c3;\n        }\n        # div2\n        {\n            padding:50px;\n            display:none;\n        }\n    &lt;/style&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div1\"&gt;Click me to show or hide the panel. &lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\"&gt;If you just meet, you can\'t be together, life is best not to meet.&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run and try it out</div>', '', 'jQuery slide', '               ', '2018-11-24 14:25:23', 'Akshay'),
(178, 12, 'jquery-animation', 'jQuery animation', '<h1>jQuery animation</h1><div>jQuery animation - animate() method</div><div><br></div><div>The jQuery animate() method is used to create custom animations.</div><div><br></div><div>grammar:</div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).animate({params},speed,callback);</div><div><br></div><div>The required params parameter defines the CSS properties that form the animation.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional speed parameter specifies the duration of the effect. It can take the following values: \"slow\", \"fast\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional callback parameter is the name of the function that is executed after the animation completes.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates a simple application of the animate() method. It moves the &lt;div&gt; element to the right by 250 pixels:</div><div><br></div><div><b>Instance&nbsp;</b></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 379px; height: 377px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").animate({left:\'250px\'});\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Start animation&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;div style=\"background:#98bf21;height:100px;width:100px;position:absolute;\"&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><div><span style=\"color: rgb(255, 0, 0);\">Tip </span>: By default, all HTML elements have a static location and are not mobile. If we need to change to, we need to set the element\'s position property to relative, fixed, or absolute!</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery animate() - manipulate multiple properties</h2><div><br></div><div>Note that multiple properties can be used simultaneously during animation generation:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 353px; height: 284px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").animate({\n                    left:\'250px\',\n                    opacity:\'0.5\',\n                    height:\'150px\',\n                    width:\'150px\'\n                });\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Start animation&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;div style=\"background:#4ae936;height:100px;width:100px;position:absolute;\"&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery animate() - use relative values</h2><div><br></div><div>You can also define a relative value that is relative to the current value of the element. You need to precede the value with += or -=:</div><div><br></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 627px; height: 400px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").animate({\n                    left:\'250px\',\n                    height:\'+=150px\',\n                    width:\'+=150px\'\n                });\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Start animation&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;div style=\"background:#98bf21;height:100px;width:100px;position:absolute;\"&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery animate() - use predefined values\n</h2><div><br></div><div>You can even set the animation value of the property to \"show\", \"hide\" or \"toggle\":</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 455px; height: 452px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").animate({\n                    height:\'toggle\'\n                });\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Start animation&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;div style=\"background:#98bf21;height:100px;width:100px;position:absolute;\"&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery animate() - use queue function</h2><div><br></div><div>By default, jQuery provides a queue function for animation.</div><div><br></div><div>This means that if you write multiple animate() calls after each other, jQuery will create an \"internal\" queue containing these method calls. Then run these animate calls one by one.</div><div><br></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 459px; height: 427px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                var div=$(\"div\");\n                div.animate({height:\'300px\',opacity:\'0.4\'},\"slow\");\n                div.animate({width:\'300px\',opacity:\'0.8\'},\"slow\");\n                div.animate({height:\'100px\',opacity:\'0.4\'},\"slow\");\n                div.animate({width:\'100px\',opacity:\'0.8\'},\"slow\");\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Start animation&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;div style=\"background:#98bf21;height:100px;width:100px;position:absolute;\"&gt;\n&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form><br></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><div>The following example moves the &lt;div&gt; element to the right by 100 pixels and then increases the font size of the text:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 456px; height: 411px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                var div=$(\"div\");\n                div.animate({left:\'100px\'},\"slow\");\n                div.animate({fontSize:\'3em\'},\"slow\");\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Start animation&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;div style=\"background:#98bf21;height:100px;width:200px;position:absolute;\"&gt;HELLO&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div>', '', 'jQuery animation', '               ', '2018-11-24 14:32:14', 'Akshay'),
(179, 12, 'jquery-stop-animation', 'jQuery stop animation', '<h1>jQuery stop animation</h1><h2>jQuery stop() method</h2><div><br></div><div>The jQuery stop() method is used to stop animations or effects before they are completed.</div><div><br></div><div>The stop() method works for all jQuery effect functions, including swipes, fades, and custom animations.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Grammar</b>:</div><div><br></div><div>$(selector).stop(stopAll,goToEnd);</div><div><br></div><div>The optional stopAll parameter specifies whether the animation queue should be cleared. The default is false, which means that only active animations are stopped, allowing any queued animation to be executed backwards.</div><div><br></div><div>The optional goToEnd parameter specifies whether the current animation is completed immediately. The default is false.</div><div><br></div><div>Therefore, by default, stop() will clear the current animation specified on the selected element.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example demonstrates the stop() method with no arguments:</div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 669px; height: 554px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"#div1\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#div2\").slideDown(5000);\n            });\n            $(\"#stop\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#div2\").stop();\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;style type=\"text/css\"&gt;\n        #Div2, #div1\n        {\n            padding:5px;\n            text-align:center;\n            background-color:#e5eecc;\n            border:solid 1px #c3c3c3;\n        }\n        #div2\n        {\n            padding:50px;\n            display:none;\n        }\n    &lt;/style&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button id=\"stop\"&gt;Stop sliding&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div1\"&gt;Click me to slide down the panel&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"div2\"&gt;We must accept disappointment because it is limited, but don\'t lose hope because it is endless.&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><h2>jQuery stop() animation (with parameters)</h2><div>&nbsp;<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 671px; height: 476px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"#start\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").animate({left:\'100px\'},5000);\n                $(\"div\").animate({fontSize:\'3em\'},5000);\n            });\n            $(\"#stop\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").stop();\n            });\n            $(\"#stop2\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").stop(true);\n            });\n            $(\"#stop3\").click(function(){\n                $(\"div\").stop(true,true);\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button id=\"start\"&gt;Start&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;button id=\"stop\"&gt;Stop&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;button id=\"stop2\"&gt;Stop all&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;button id=\"stop3\"&gt;Stop the animation, but complete the action&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Click the \"Start\" button to start the animation. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Click the \"Stop\" button to stop the currently active animation, but then we can activate it again in the animation queue. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Click the \"Stop All\" button to stop the current animation and clear the animation queue, so all animations for the element will stop. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Click \"Stop animation, but complete the action\" to quickly complete the action and stop it. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;div style=\"background:#98bf21;height:100px;width:200px;position:absolute;\"&gt;HELLO&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div>', '', 'jQuery stop animation', '               ', '2018-11-24 14:38:44', 'Akshay'),
(180, 12, 'jquery-callback', 'jQuery callback', '<h1>jQuery Callback</h1><div>The Callback function is executed after the current animation is 100% complete.</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery animation problem</h2><div><br></div><div>Many jQuery functions involve animation. These functions may have speed or duration as optional parameters.</div><div><br></div><div>例子：$(\"p\").hide(\"slow\")</div><div>The speed or duration parameter can be set to many different values, such as \"slow\", \"fast\", \"normal\" or milliseconds.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Instance</b></div><div><br></div><div>The following example callback function after the hidden effect is fully implemented:</div><div><br></div><div>Use a callback instance&nbsp;</div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 423px; height: 371px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"p\").hide(\"slow\",function(){\n                    Alert(\"The paragraph is now hidden\");\n                });\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Hide&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Tell yourself that you can\'t be mad and lazy now, and the future is important. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div><div><br></div><div>The following example does not have a callback function, and the warning box will pop up before the hidden effect is completed:</div><div><br></div><h2>No callback</h2><div><br></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 418px; height: 288px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function(){\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"p\").hide(1000);\n                Alert (\"The paragraph is now hidden\");\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;Hide&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Learn from everyone, but don\'t imitate anyone&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run the program and try it out</div>', '', 'jQuery callback', '               ', '2018-11-24 14:41:31', 'Akshay');
INSERT INTO `lesson_post` (`id`, `sub_cat_id`, `slug`, `post_title`, `post`, `seo_keyword`, `seo_title`, `seo_description`, `last_updated`, `updated_by`) VALUES
(181, 12, 'jquery-chaining', 'jQuery Chaining', '		  <h1>jQuery Chaining</h1><div>With jQuery, you can link actions/methods together.</div><div><br></div><div>Chaining allows us to run multiple jQuery methods (on the same element) in one statement.</div><div><br></div><h2>jQuery method link</h2><div><br></div><div>Until now, we have written one jQuery statement at a time (one after the other).</div><div><br></div><div>However, there is a technique called chaining that allows us to run multiple jQuery commands on the same element, one after the other.</div><div><br></div><div>Tip : In this case, the browser does not have to find the same element multiple times.</div><div><br></div><div>To link an action, simply add the action to the previous action.</div><div><br></div><div>The following example links css(), slideUp(), and slideDown() together. The \"p1\" element will first turn red, then swipe up, then swipe down:</div><div><br></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 510px; height: 218px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n&lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n&lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;script&gt;\n$(document).ready(function()\n  {\n  $(\"button\").click(function(){\n    $(\"#p1\").css(\"color\",\"red\").slideUp(2000).slideDown(2000);\n  });\n});\n&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n\n&lt;p id=\"p1\"&gt;jquerylearn.com!!&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;point me&lt;/button&gt;\n\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run and try it out</div><div><br></div><div>If necessary, we can also add multiple method calls.</div><div><br></div><div>Tip: When you link, the line of code becomes very poor. However, the jQuery syntax is not very strict; you can write in the desired format, including line breaks and indents.</div><div><br></div><div>The following writing can also work well:</div><div><br></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 534px; height: 395px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"utf-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\"&gt;\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(document).ready(function()\n        {\n            $(\"button\").click(function(){\n                $(\"#p1\").css(\"color\",\"red\")\n                        .slideUp(2000)\n                        .slideDown(2000);\n            });\n        });\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;p id=\"p1\"&gt;jquerylearn.com!!&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;button&gt;point me&lt;/button&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>Run and try it out</div><div><br></div><div>Hint : jQuery will throw away extra spaces and treat it as a line of long code to execute the above line of code.</div> \n		  ', '', 'jQuery Chaining', '                 ', '2018-11-24 14:46:26', 'Akshay'),
(171, 11, 'jquery-syntax', 'jQuery syntax', '<h1>jQuery syntax&nbsp;</h1><div><br></div><div>In jQuery programs, whether it is the selection of page elements or built-in function functions, it starts with the dollar sign \"$\", and this \"$\" is the most important and unique object in jQuery: jQuery object, So we can write this when the page element selects or executes a function:</div><div><br></div><pre>$(function(){}); //Execute an anonymous function</pre><pre>$(\'#box\'); //Select the ID element to execute</pre><pre>$(\'#box\').css(\'color\',\'red\'); //Execute function function</pre><div>Since \"$\" itself is an abbreviation for jQuery object, then the above code can be written as follows:</div><div><br></div><pre>jQuery(function(){});</pre><pre>jQuery(\'#box\');</pre><pre>jQuery(\'#box\').css(\'color\',\'red\');</pre><div><br></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 395px; height: 331px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;Form&lt;/title&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n        $(function(){\n            $(\'#box\').css(\'color\',\'red\');\n        });\n// alert($===jQuery);\n &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"box\"&gt;jQuery syntax&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div>\n\n</div><div></div>\n\n\n<p></p><p><br></p><h2>jQuery loading mode</h2><p>We have been using $(function(){}) in the previous code; this code is wrapped first and last, do you know why you should do this?</p><p>The reason is that our jQuery library file is loaded before the body element, we have to wait for all the webpage code to load before we can load the JavaScript code, otherwise we can\'t get it.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p><b>Instance</b></p><p></p>\n\n<form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 844px; height: 165px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;Form&lt;/title&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n            $(\'#box\').css(\'color\',\'red\');\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"box\"&gt;jQuery syntax&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n</textarea>\n\n</form><br><p></p>So our previous JavaScript gave us:<pre><br>Window.onload=function(){}; //JavaScript waits for loading</pre><div>Our jQuery gives us:</div><div><br></div><pre>$(document).ready(function(){}); //jQuery waits for loading</pre><div><br></div><div><h2>The difference between the two:</h2><div><br></div><h3>1. Timing of execution</h3><div><br></div><div>Window.onload : You must wait for the page to load (including the image) to execute the package code.</div><div><br></div><div>$(document).ready(function(){}) : Just wait for the DOM structure in the page to load and execute the package code. Higher effect</div><div><br></div><h3>2. Number of executions</h3><div><br></div><div>Window.onload can only be executed once, if the second time, then the first execution will be overwritten</div><div><br></div><div>$(document).ready(function(){}) : will not be overwritten no matter how many times it is executed</div><div><br></div><div><b>Example</b></div><div><form method=\"POST\" class=\"execute\" action=\"../lab\"><textarea name=\"data\" class=\"code\" style=\"margin: 0px; width: 528px; height: 152px;\">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;\n&lt;html lang=\"en\"&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n    &lt;meta charset=\"UTF-8\"&gt;\n    &lt;title&gt;Form&lt;/title&gt;\n    &lt;script src=\"https://libs.baidu.com/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js\" type=\"text/javascript\"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n    &lt;script&gt;\n// window.onload=function(){\n// alert(1)\n// };\n// window.onload=function(){\n// alert(2)\n// };\n $(document).ready(function(){\n            alert(\'1\')\n        });\n         $(document).ready(function(){\n              alert(\'2\')\n         })\n    &lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;\n&lt;div id=\"box\"&gt;jQuery syntax&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;/body&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;</textarea></form></div><div><h3>3. Shorthand</h3><div><br></div><pre>Window.onload<br>$(document).ready(function(){}) $(function (){});</pre><div><br></div><div>In practical applications, we rarely use window.onload directly, because it needs to wait for large elements such as images to be loaded before executing JS code. If the network speed is slow, the page is fully expanded. The image is still loading slowly, and any JS interactions on the page are all in a suspended state, such as some drop-down menus.&nbsp;</div></div></div>', '', 'jQuery syntax', '             ', '2018-11-24 13:22:20', 'Akshay');
